"The importance of a laser-specific Ideal Customer Profile (not hazy personas) has a ton of downstream effects". 

In this week's edition of "what he/she said" I am sharing this excellent post by Ken Oestreich.

To add on to Ken Oestreich argument, and the excellent visual from Rahim Kaba from Gartner, we have clear proof of this.

Rahim Kaba, we have shared some of our work with your colleague Hank Barnes at Gartner.

When Zsuzsanna Ferenczi and I here at Bunes & Ferenczi look at both ICP creation and ranking we see consistently that between 25% to 35% of the accounts you believe are ICP are not.

They are actually a poor fit. 

We have done this using both AI/ML modelling from Dun & Bradstreet Europe across +20,000 accounts for Fortune 500 clients, and...

Simpler triage process of existing Target Account Lists (TAL) using a list of binary ICP criteria combined with stack ranking. 

Great post Ken Oestreich, and keep up the conversation loudly.

So, even the people in the back can hear this.

Building and maintaining a good credit score is crucial for the success of any business. 

Here‚Äôs a quick guide to help you get started and keep your credit in top shape:

Credit: capitalxpand 

üëâ Follow for more insights on building and maintaining strong business credit! üöÄ

1Ô∏è‚É£ Establish Your Business Entity: Start by legally registering your business as an LLC, S Corp, or sole proprietorship. This step is fundamental to establishing your business‚Äôs credibility.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Obtain an EIN: Your Employer Identification Number (EIN) is like a social security number for your business. It‚Äôs essential for opening bank accounts and applying for credit.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Open a Business Bank Account: This separates your personal and business finances, which is critical for managing cash flow and demonstrating financial responsibility to lenders.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Apply for Business Credit Cards: Start with small business credit cards or a line of credit from your bank. Use these responsibly to build a positive credit history.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Pay Bills on Time: Timely payments are crucial. They make up a significant portion of your credit score and demonstrate to lenders that you are reliable.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Monitor Your Credit: Regularly check your business credit score through platforms like Dun & Bradstreet, Experian, or Equifax. This helps you stay informed about your credit standing and detect any errors or fraudulent activity early.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Limit Credit Inquiries: Each credit application can slightly lower your score. Apply only when necessary and spread out your applications over time.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Maintain Low Credit Utilization: Keep your credit card balances low relative to your credit limits. High balances can negatively impact your score.

Building business credit takes time and discipline, but with these steps, you‚Äôre on your way to financial success. Stay proactive, make informed decisions, and watch your credit score soar!

Segmenting your Ideal Customer Profile (ICPs) on a single firmographic variable is dangerous.

Zsuzsanna Ferenczi and I here at Bunes & Ferenczi have been on our soapboxes for years on this.

I know legacy tech firms with +$20bn in revenue who segment their Dun & Bradstreet Master Data based upon employee count alone.

We advocate an "and/or" logic when integrating firmographic into your segmentation:
‚úî Number of employees and/or
‚úî Revenue and/or
‚úî Total assets and/or
‚úî Number of subsidiaries and/or
‚úî Number of operating countries and/or
‚úî Vertical/industry codes and/or
You get it.

Let me give you the perfect example of this, even when everything is in the public.

I was asked today to investigate an entity in the Nordics for a potential business opportunity for one of my fractional engagements:
‚ùå LinkedIn says 95 employees
‚ùå Enento Group's Proff service says 55 employees
‚ùå I downloaded the annual report from Proff, and it says 16 employees (which is self-reported)
‚ùå I manually count the number of profiles listed on their website and it is 38 employees

So where do you segment when the range is 16 to 95?

Who do you believe?

Which is why you need the "and/or logic".

Stop segmenting on one variable.

Yes, even you Fortune 500 company.

Jans Aasman is speaking at The AI Tech Symposium!

The AI Tech Symposium is a virtual conference taking place on July 18-19th showcasing real AI system case studies as shared by seasoned practioners.

Jans is the CEO at Franz Inc.

AREA OF SPECIALIZATION:
His area of expertise is in intelligent user interfaces and applied artificial intelligence projects with a focus on leveraging knowledge graphs and other semantic technology.

TRACK RECORD OF SUCCESS:
- Started his career as an experimental and cognitive psychologist, earning his PhD in cognitive science with a detailed model of car driver behavior using Lisp and Soar.¬†
- Spent a large part of professional life in telecommunications research.¬†
- Gathered patents in the areas of speech technology, multimodal user interaction, recommendation engines while developing early versions of the iPad and Siri (yes, unfortunately many years too early :-)¬†
- From 1995 to 2004 taught as a part-time professor in the Industrial Design department of the Delft University of Technology.
- Evangelist for Franz Inc.'s semantic graph database (AllegroGraph) and their enterprise development environment (Allegro Common Lisp)
- Spoken extensively at events such as Semantic Technologies Conference, International Semantic Web Conference, Java One, Enterprise Data World, Semantics in Healthcare and Life Sciences, Linked Data Planet, INSA, GeoWeb, AAAI, NoSQLNow, Graph Data Management, RuleML, IEEE conferences, and DEBS to name a few.

NOTABLE ACCOMPLISHMENTS INCLUDE:
As both a scientist and CEO, Dr. Aasman continues to break ground in the areas of Artificial Intelligence and Knowledge Graphs as he works hand-in-hand with numerous Fortune 500 organizations as well as government entities worldwide, including: Deloitte, Credit Suisse, Australian Government (Department of Defense), National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency, Stanford University, Merck, AstraZeneca, Franklin Templeton, Jefferies, Ford Motor Company, Dun & Bradstreet, NASA - National Aeronautics and Space Administration, Wolters Kluwer, and Wells Fargo to name a few!

EDUCATIONAL BACKGROUND:
- PhD in Cognitive Science from the University of Groningen
- His main research topics were around the measurement of mental effort and stress through heart rate variability. One of his most cited paper came from this period: "Operator effort and the measurement of heart-rate variability" (Aasman, Mulder, Mulder, 1987, Human Factors)

===================================

Purchase your ticket for The AI Tech Symposium now at:
https://bit.ly/3Ve03K2

This week gave me a career highlight moment and I'm still buzzing from it! Thank you so much to Ayesha Ansari for inviting me to speak on a panel event where we bought together Sage's UK&I Gender Alliance & Women in Data UK groups, with Dun & Bradstreet Europe's UK Women's Network. I loved sharing the stage with such inspiring leaders that each shared their views on the evolving Data industry trends from the perspectives of their own functions Amy Abbott (Legal), Sara de la Torre (Sales) and Katie Thomas (PR). It was an incredible opportunity to showcase the diverse career paths of female leadership in the data industry and share some tips and lessons learnt.
A big shout-out to everyone who attended in person and online, and contributed to the enriching discussions. Let's continue to uplift each other and pave the way for more women in data!
#WomenInData #Leadership #GenderAlliance
Name: Rebecca Gillingham
